ce:section.ce:para:
Inspired by the developments of low-temperature synthesis of CDs and the features of FIA, herein, fluorescent carbon dots derived at room temperature (R-CDs) were prepared via Schiff base dehydration reaction of sodium ascorbate and polyethyleneimine (Scheme 1
                     ). R-CDs were characterized by transmission electron microscope (TEM), Fourier transform infrared spectrometer (FT-IR), X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS), ultraviolet and visible spectrophotometry (UV–vis absorption), and fluorescence spectroscopy to evaluate their morphology, chemical functional groups, chemical composition and optical properties. Furthermore, the formation mechanism of R-CDs was proposed and verified. Analysis of photoluminescent behavior of R-CDs revealed the fluorescence quenching of R-CDs by nitrite was unaffected in the presence of high NaCl concentration. Subsequently, this reaction was combined with an asynchronous-alternating merging-zone FIA, providing a simple, accurate, automatic fluorescence system for nitrite determination (FI-FL-NO2
                     −). The presented method was used for the detection of nitrite in the pickling process of Sichuan preserved vegetables.
